{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621242"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:51:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:51:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16681"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16681"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0,1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70372"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9372"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16681"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55836"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5498"},{"type":"tags","id":"12918"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23628"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70372"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA junior doctor is examining a patient with cellulitis in the Emergency Department. The patient\u0027s wound dressing needs to be changed, and several other patients are waiting to be seen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes when hand hygiene should be performed as part of standard precautions?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Only after direct patient contact","Only before sterile procedures","Only when hands are visibly soiled","Before and after patient contact","Only after removing gloves"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is to perform hand hygiene \u003Cstrong\u003Ebefore and after patient contact\u003C/strong\u003E. This is one of the five moments for hand hygiene and is essential for preventing transmission of microorganisms between patients and healthcare workers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly after direct patient contact\u003C/strong\u003E - Performing hand hygiene only after contact fails to protect patients from organisms that may be carried by healthcare workers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly before sterile procedures\u003C/strong\u003E - While hand hygiene is crucial before sterile procedures, it is required for all patient interactions to prevent cross-contamination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly when hands are visibly soiled\u003C/strong\u003E - Pathogenic microorganisms are present even when hands appear clean, making regular hand hygiene essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly after removing gloves\u003C/strong\u003E - Hand hygiene is required both before and after glove use, as gloves alone do not provide complete protection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe World Health Organisation\u0027s five moments for hand hygiene are: before patient contact, before clean/aseptic procedures, after body fluid exposure risk, after patient contact, and after touching patient surroundings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Standard precautions include hand hygiene, personal protective equipment, safe injection practices, respiratory hygiene, and environmental cleaning.","Hand hygiene must be performed before and after patient contact, before clean/aseptic procedures, after body fluid exposure, and after touching patient surroundings.","Personal protective equipment includes gloves, gowns, masks and eye protection based on anticipated exposure risk."],"references":["5 moments for hand hygiene. Australian Commission on Safety and Quality in Healthcare. https://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/our-work/infection-prevention-and-control/national-hand-hygiene-initiative/what-hand-hygiene/5-moments-hand-hygiene"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55836"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16681"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55836"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T20:02:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T20:04:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9372"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70372"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,